By DIANA HENRIQUES and GUILBERT GATES

Once, insider trading was considered a crime of opportunity — a chance to profit from an unexpected tip. Today, regulators fear it has become a business model for some hedge funds on Wall Street. In the last six months, nearly two dozen people have been accused of participating in a complex marketplace where inside information was regularly bought and sold.

Some defendants have pleaded guilty; others deny the charges, saying they profited from dogged research, not illegal tips.

